The functionalization of the CD was also analyzed using 1H NMR spectroscopy (Fig. 4
                        ). In the spectrum of ecPis-4s (Fig. 4b) the region between 7.9 and 8.6 ppm corresponds to resonances of the amide hydrogens while the aromatic hydrogens resonances are observed in the range of 7.0–7.6 ppm. The alpha hydrogens (Hα) signals are observed between 3.5 and 4.3 ppm, whereas resonances of the side chain hydrogens in the range of 0.8–3.2 ppm. The 1H NMR spectrum obtained for the CD reveals the presence of characteristic signals from several functional groups. The region comprised between 0.5 and 3 ppm is attributed to the resonances of hydrogens bound to sp
                        3 carbons, the region between 3 and 4 ppm to the 1H resonances of hydroxyl, alpha CO ether and/or carbonyl groups, and the region between 6 and 10 ppm to the aromatic and formyl aldehyde hydrogens [42]. Typical 1H chemical shifts of side chains, Hα, amide (HN) and aromatic groups of the peptide are also noticed in the spectrum of the CD@ecPis-4s, confirming the obtainment of the CD-peptide-decorated nanoparticles.
